### 📌 Image 3 — Spring Boot Layered Architecture

```
Client
  │
  └──► localhost:8080/about (HTTP request)
           │
    ┌──────▼──────────────────────────┐
    │         Spring Boot App          │
    │  ┌───────────┐  ┌─────────────┐ │
    │  │ Controller│→ │Service Layer│ │
    │  └───────────┘  └──────┬──────┘ │
    │                  ┌─────▼──────┐ │
    │                  │    Repo    │ │
    │                  └─────┬──────┘ │
    └────────────────────────┼────────┘
                             ▼
                           [ DB ]
  ◄──── response back to Client
```

**Each layer is a Java class:**
- `class Controller { ... }` → handles HTTP, has an **object** of Service
- `class Service { Service() { ... } }` → business logic
- Repo → talks to DB

**Key insight:** Each layer depends on the next — Spring injects these dependencies automatically using `@Autowired`, so you never manually `new` them.

---

### 🔑 One-Line Summary
> Spring's IoC container manages object lifecycle; DI injects dependencies between layers (Controller → Service → Repo → DB), keeping your code loosely coupled.
